[32m"Masked text for sample 2, segment 4993-5492: .\n\nLet me try again.\n\nTo determine the minimum temperature of the second bottle, we need to use the information provided about Donny's ability to drink the water. Donny can only drink water if it's at least 40 degrees. He has two mugs of water. One mug is 33 degrees, and the other is an unknown temperature \\(T\\). When he pours 4 ounces of water from the 33-degree mug and 1 ounce from the \\(T\\)-degree mug into his water bottle, the resulting mixture must be at least 40 degrees for him to drink it.\n\nThe temperature of the resulting mixture can be calculated using the weighted average of the temperatures of the two mugs. The formula for the temperature \\(T_{\\text{mix}}\\) of the mixture is:\n\n\\[ T_{\\text{mix}} = \\frac{4 \\cdot 33 + 1 \\cdot T}{4 + 1} \\]\n\nWe know that \\(T_{\\text{mix}}\\) must be at least 40 degrees. So we can set up the inequality:\n\n\\[ \\frac{4 \\cdot 33 + 1 \\cdot T}{5} \\geq 40 \\]\n\nSolving this inequality will give us the minimum temperature \\(T\\) of the second bottle.\n\nLet's solve it step by step:\n\n1. Multiply both sides by 5 to clear the fraction:\n\\[ 4 \\cdot 33 + 1 \\cdot T \\geq 40 \\cdot 5 \\]\n\n2. Simplify the right side:\n\\[ 4 \\cdot 33 + T \\geq 200 \\]\n\n3. Simplify the left side:\n\\[ 132 + T \\geq 200 \\]\n\n4. Subtract 132 from both sides:\n\\[ T \\geq 200 - 132 \\]\n\\[ T \\geq 68 \\]\n\nSo, the minimum temperature of the second bottle is 68 degrees. Let's confirm this using Python code.\n```python\n# Calculate the minimum temperature of the second bottle\nT_min = 200 - 4 * 33\nprint(T_min)\n```\n```output\n68\n```\nThe minimum temperature of the second bottle is \\(\\boxed{68}\\) degrees.\n\nWait, let me recheck my solution.\n\n"[0m
