\n\\]\n\nFirst, simplify the constant terms:\n\n1. Calculate \\(3 \\times 5^2\\):\n   \\[\n   3 \\times 25 = 75\n   \\]\n\n2. The equation becomes:\n   \\[\n   75 - \\frac{4(5-a)^2}{3} = 63\n   \\]\n\n3. Rearrange the equation to isolate the term involving \\(a\\):\n   \\[\n   \\frac{4(5-a)^2}{3} = 75 - 63\n   \\]\n\n4. Simplify the right side:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{4(5-a)^2}{3} = 12\n   \\]\n\n5. Multiply both sides by 3 to eliminate the fraction:\n   \\[\n   4(5-a)^2 = 36\n   \\]\n\n6. Divide both sides by 4:\n   \\[\n   (5-a)^2 = 9\n   \\]\n\n7. Take the square root of both sides:\n   \\[\n   5-a = \\pm 3\n   \\]\n\nThis results in two possible equations:\n\n- \\(5-a = 3\\)\n- \\(5-a = -3\\)\n\nSolve each equation for \\(a\\):\n\n1. For \\(5-a = 3\\):\n   \\[\n   a = 5 - 3 = 2\n   \\]\n\n2. For \\(5-a = -3\\):\n   \\[\n   a = 5 + 3 = 8\n   \\]\n\nThe values of \\(a\\) that satisfy the equation are 2 and 8. The sum of these values is:\n\n\\[\n2 + 8 = 10\n\\]\n\nTherefore, the given answer of 10 is correct.<|im_end|>\n"[0m
