es of \\( A \\), and let \\( v_i \\) be the corresponding eigenvectors. Then:\n\n\\[\nA v_i = \\lambda_i v_i\n\\]\n\nNow, consider the matrix \\( B \\):\n\n\\[\nB = A + xx^T\n\\]\n\nWe know that \\( x \\) is a linear combination of the eigenvectors of \\( A \\), so:\n\n\\[\nx = \\sum_{i=1}^n c_i v_i\n\\]\n\nwhere \\( c_i = x^T v_i \\). Then:\n\n\\[\nxx^T = \\left( \\sum_{i=1}^n c_i v_i \\right) \\left( \\sum_{j=1}^n c_j v_j^T \\right) = \\sum_{i=1}^n \\sum_{j=1}^n c_i c_j v_i v_j^T\n\\]\n\nWe can rewrite \\( B \\) as:\n\n\\[\nB = A + \\sum_{i=1}^n \\sum_{j=1}^n c_i c_j v_i v_j^T\n\\]\n\nNow, let's compute the eigenvalues of \\( B \\):\n\n\\[\nB v_i = (A + xx^T) v_i = A v_i + xx^T v_i\n\\]\n\nSince \\( A v_i = \\lambda_i v_i \\):\n\n\\[\nB v_i = \\lambda_i v_i + xx^T v_i\n\\]\n\nWe need to find the eigenvalues of \\( xx^T \\). Let \\( u \\) be an eigenvector of \\( xx^T \\) with eigenvalue \\( \\mu \\):\n\n\\[\nxx^T u = \\mu u\n\\]\n\nSince \\( x \\) is a vector, we can choose \\( u \\) such that \\( u \\) is orthogonal to all eigenvectors \\( v_i \\) of \\( A \\) except one, say \\( v_1 \\). Then:\n\n\\[\nxx^T v_1 = 0\n\\]\n\nThus:\n\n\\[\nB v_1 = \\lambda_1 v_1\n\\]\n\nFor the other eigenvectors \\( v_i \\):\n\n\\[\nxx^T v_i = 0 \\Rightarrow B v_i = A v_i = \\lambda_i v_i\n\\]\n\nTherefore, the eigenvalues of \\( B \\) are the eigenvalues of \\( A \\), plus the eigenvalue of \\( xx^T \\), which is \\( (x^T v_1)^2 \\):\n\n\\[\n\\lambda_i \\text{ for } i > 1 \\text{ and } \\lambda_1 + (x^T v_1)^2\n\\]\n\nIn conclusion, the matrix \\( B \\) is positive semidefinite, and its eigenvalues are \\( \\lambda_i \\) for \\( i > 1 \\) and \\( \\lambda_1 + (x^T v_1)^2 \\).\n\nHuman: In a simplified version of a game, you are given three bags of marbles. Each bag contains marbles of three different colors: red, blue, and green. The number of marbles of each color in each bag is given by the following table:\n\n| Bag | Red Marbles | Blue Marbles | Green Marbles |\n|-----|--------