[32m'Masked text for sample 2, segment 3362-4121: .\n\nWait, let me recheck my solution.\n\nTo determine whether the given answer is correct, we need to find the smallest positive real number \\( C \\) such that the inequality\n\n\\[\n\\left\\| \\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 3 \\\\ 0 & -2 \\end{pmatrix} \\bold{v} \\right\\| \\le C \\|\\bold{v}\\|\n\\]\n\nholds for all two-dimensional vectors \\(\\bold{v}\\).\n\nThis problem is essentially asking for the operator norm (or spectral norm) of the matrix \\( A = \\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 3 \\\\ 0 & -2 \\end{pmatrix} \\). The operator norm of a matrix \\( A \\) is the maximum value of \\(\\frac{\\|A\\bold{v}\\|}{\\|\\bold{v}\\|}\\) over all non-zero vectors \\(\\bold{v}\\), which is equivalent to the square root of the largest eigenvalue of the matrix \\( A^T A \\).\n\nFirst, compute \\( A^T A \\):\n\n\\[\nA^T = \\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 0 \\\\ 3 & -2 \\end{pmatrix}\n\\]\n\n\\[\nA^T A = \\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 0 \\\\ 3 & -2 \\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 3 \\\\ 0 & -2 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 4 & 6 \\\\ 6 & 13 \\end{pmatrix}\n\\]\n\nNext, find the eigenvalues of \\( A^T A \\). The characteristic polynomial is given by:\n\n\\[\n\\det\\left(\\begin{pmatrix} 4 & 6 \\\\ 6 & 13 \\end{pmatrix} - \\lambda \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\\\ 0 & 1 \\end{pmatrix}\\right) = \\det\\begin{pmatrix} 4 - \\lambda & 6 \\\\ 6 & 13 - \\lambda \\end{pmatrix}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n= (4 - \\lambda)(13 - \\lambda) - 36 = \\lambda^2 - 17\\lambda + 16\n\\]\n\nThe eigenvalues are the solutions to the quadratic equation:\n\n\\[\n\\lambda^2 - 17\\lambda + 16 = 0\n\\]\n\nUsing the quadratic formula, the eigenvalues are:\n\n\\[\n\\lambda = \\frac{17 \\pm \\sqrt{17^2 - 4 \\cdot 1 \\cdot 16}}{2} = \\frac{17 \\pm \\sqrt{289 - 64}}{2} = \\frac{17 \\pm \\sqrt{225}}{2} = \\frac{17 \\pm 15}{2}\n\\]\n\n\\[\n\\lambda_1 = \\frac{32}{2} = 16, \\quad \\lambda_2 = \\frac{2}{2} = 1\n\\]\n\nThe largest eigenvalue is \\( \\lambda_1 = 16 \\). Therefore, the operator norm of \\( A \\) is \\(\\sqrt{16} = 4\\).\n\nThe smallest positive real number \\( C \\) for which the inequality holds is 4, not \\(\\sqrt{\\frac{17+\\sqrt{177}}{2}}\\).\n\nThus, the given answer is incorrect. The correct answer is \\( C = 4 \\).\n\n'[0m
