[32m"Masked text for sample 2, segment 940-1469: .\n\nLet me try again.\n\nAn old wooden device has three rotating discs with digits printed on them in the order shown above. Each disc rotates independently at a constant speed. The first disc completes a full rotation in 10 seconds, the second in 15 seconds, and the third in 20 seconds. How long does it take for the discs to show the sequence 111 again after they start rotating simultaneously? \\boxed{}. \\rangle\nTo find out how long it takes for the discs to show the sequence 111 again, we need to determine the least common multiple (LCM) of the rotation times of the three discs. This is because the discs will align again only after a time that is a multiple of all their individual rotation periods.\n\nThe rotation times of the discs are:\n- First disc: 10 seconds\n- Second disc: 15 seconds\n- Third disc: 20 seconds\n\nWe will use the `math` library to find the LCM. The LCM of two numbers \\(a\\) and \\(b\\) can be calculated using the greatest common divisor (GCD) with the formula:\n\\[ \\text{lcm}(a, b) = \\frac{|a \\cdot b|}{\\text{gcd}(a, b)} \\]\n\nTo find the LCM of three numbers \\(a\\), \\(b\\), and \\(c\\), we can first find the LCM of \\(a\\) and \\(b\\), and then find the LCM of that result with \\(c\\).\n\nLet's calculate it step-by-step using Python.\n```python\nimport math\nfrom functools import reduce\n\n# Function to calculate LCM of two numbers\ndef lcm(a, b):\n    return abs(a * b) // math.gcd(a, b)\n\n# Function to calculate LCM of a list of numbers\ndef lcm_multiple(numbers):\n    return reduce(lcm, numbers)\n\n# Rotation times of the discs\nrotation_times = [10, 15, 20]\n\n# Calculate the LCM of the rotation times\nlcm_time = lcm_multiple(rotation_times)\nprint(lcm_time)\n```\n```output\n60\n```\nThe least common multiple (LCM) of the rotation times 10, 15, and 20 seconds is 60 seconds. Therefore, it will take 60 seconds for the discs to show the sequence 111 again after they start rotating simultaneously.\n\nThe final answer is \\(\\boxed{60}\\).\n\nWait, let me recheck my solution.\n\n"[0m
