[32m'Masked text for sample 3, segment 4966-5424: .\n\nLet me try again.\n\nIn $\\triangle ABC$, we have $AB = 13$, $BC = 14$, and $AC = 15$.  Let $M$ be the midpoint of $\\overline{BC}$.  Find $AM$. 1. Understand the Problem:\n   - $\\triangle PQR$ is isosceles with $PQ = QR = 34$ and $PR = 32$.\n   - We need to find the length of the median $\\overline{QM}$, where $M$ is the midpoint of $\\overline{PR}$.\n\n2. Identify Key Concepts:\n   - In an isosceles triangle, the median to the base is also an altitude, angle bisector, and perpendicular bisector.\n   - The median divides the triangle into two smaller triangles of equal area.\n\n3. Calculate the Length of $\\overline{QM}$:\n   - Since $M$ is the midpoint of $\\overline{PR}$, $PM = MR = \\frac{PR}{2} = \\frac{32}{2} = 16$.\n   - $\\overline{QM}$ is the median to the base $PR$, so it is perpendicular to $PR$ and bisects $PR$.\n   - $\\triangle PQM$ and $\\triangle QRM$ are right triangles because $\\overline{QM}$ is the median to the base of an isosceles triangle.\n\n4. Use the Pythagorean Theorem:\n   - In right triangle $\\triangle PQM$, we have $PQ = 34$ and $PM = 16$.\n   - By the Pythagorean theorem:\n     $$\n     QM = \\sqrt{PQ^2 - PM^2} = \\sqrt{34^2 - 16^2} = \\sqrt{1156 - 256} = \\sqrt{900} = 30.\n     $$\n\n5. Conclusion:\n   - The length of the median $\\overline{QM}$ is $30$.\n\nAnswer: $\\boxed{30}$\n\nWait, let me recheck my solution.\n\n'[0m
