[32m"Masked text for sample 2, segment 4120-5075: ).\n\nLet me try again.\n\nTo find the smallest positive real number \\( C \\) for which the inequality\n\\[\n\\left\\| \\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 3 \\\\ 0 & -2 \\end{pmatrix} \\mathbf{v} \\right\\| \\le C \\|\\mathbf{v}\\|\n\\]\nholds for all two-dimensional vectors \\(\\mathbf{v}\\), we need to determine the operator norm of the matrix \\(\\mathbf{A} = \\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 3 \\\\ 0 & -2 \\end{pmatrix}\\).\n\nThe operator norm of a matrix \\(\\mathbf{A}\\) is the maximum value of \\(\\frac{\\|\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{v}\\|}{\\|\\mathbf{v}\\|}\\) for any non-zero vector \\(\\mathbf{v}\\). In other words, it is the maximum singular value of \\(\\mathbf{A}\\).\n\nThe singular values of a matrix \\(\\mathbf{A}\\) are the square roots of the eigenvalues of \\(\\mathbf{A}^T \\mathbf{A}\\). Let's compute \\(\\mathbf{A}^T \\mathbf{A}\\):\n\\[\n\\mathbf{A}^T \\mathbf{A} = \\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 0 \\\\ 3 & -2 \\end{pmatrix} \\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 3 \\\\ 0 & -2 \\end{pmatrix} = \\begin{pmatrix} 4 & 6 \\\\ 6 & 13 \\end{pmatrix}.\n\\]\nThe eigenvalues of \\(\\mathbf{A}^T \\mathbf{A}\\) are the roots of the characteristic polynomial:\n\\[\n\\det\\left( \\begin{pmatrix} 4 & 6 \\\\ 6 & 13 \\end{pmatrix} - \\lambda \\begin{pmatrix} 1 & 0 \\\\ 0 & 1 \\end{pmatrix} \\right) = \\det\\left( \\begin{pmatrix} 4 - \\lambda & 6 \\\\ 6 & 13 - \\lambda \\end{pmatrix} \\right) = (4 - \\lambda)(13 - \\lambda) - 36 = \\lambda^2 - 17\\lambda + 16.\n\\]\nThe roots of the characteristic polynomial are:\n\\[\n\\lambda = \\frac{17 \\pm \\sqrt{17^2 - 4 \\cdot 16}}{2} = \\frac{17 \\pm \\sqrt{289 - 64}}{2} = \\frac{17 \\pm \\sqrt{225}}{2} = \\frac{17 \\pm 15}{2}.\n\\]\nSo, the eigenvalues are \\(\\lambda_1 = 16\\) and \\(\\lambda_2 = 1\\). The singular values of \\(\\mathbf{A}\\) are the square roots of these eigenvalues, so they are \\(\\sqrt{16} = 4\\) and \\(\\sqrt{1} = 1\\). The maximum singular value is 4, so the operator norm of \\(\\mathbf{A}\\) is 4.\n\nTherefore, the smallest positive real number \\(C\\) for which the inequality holds is \\(C = 4\\).\n\nLet's verify this using Python code to ensure the result is accurate.\n```python\nimport numpy as np\n\n# Define the matrix A\nA = np.array([[2, 3], [0, -2]])\n\n# Compute the operator norm of A\noperator_norm = np.linalg.norm(A, 2)\nprint(operator_norm)\n```\n```output\n4.0\n```\nThe operator norm of the matrix \\(\\mathbf{A} = \\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 3 \\\\ 0 & -2 \\end{pmatrix}\\) is indeed \\(4.0\\). Therefore, the smallest positive real number \\(C\\) for which\n\\[\n\\left\\| \\begin{pmatrix} 2 & 3 \\\\ 0 & -2 \\end{pmatrix} \\mathbf{v} \\right\\| \\le C \\|\\mathbf{v}\\|\n\\]\nholds for all two-dimensional vectors \\(\\mathbf{v}\\) is \\(\\boxed{4}\\).\n\nWait, let me recheck my solution.\n\n"[0m
