[32m'Masked text for sample 3, segment 2158-2770: .\n\nLet me try again.\n\nGiven:\n1. $\\log_6 (x-y) + \\log_6 (x+y) = 2$\n2. $\\log_y 5x = 2$\n\nStep 1: Simplify the first equation\n$$\\log_6 (x-y) + \\log_6 (x+y) = 2$$\nUsing the property of logarithms $\\log_b a + \\log_b c = \\log_b (ac)$,\n$$\\log_6 [(x-y)(x+y)] = 2$$\nSimplify the expression inside the logarithm:\n$$\\log_6 (x^2 - y^2) = 2$$\nConvert the logarithmic equation to an exponential equation:\n$$6^2 = x^2 - y^2$$\n$$36 = x^2 - y^2$$\n$$x^2 - y^2 = 36$$\n\nStep 2: Simplify the second equation\n$$\\log_y 5x = 2$$\nConvert the logarithmic equation to an exponential equation:\n$$y^2 = 5x$$\n\nStep 3: Solve the system of equations\nWe now have a system of equations:\n1. $x^2 - y^2 = 36$\n2. $y^2 = 5x$\n\nSubstitute $y^2$ from equation 2 into equation 1:\n$$x^2 - 5x = 36$$\nRearrange to form a quadratic equation:\n$$x^2 - 5x - 36 = 0$$\n\nFactor the quadratic equation:\n$$(x - 9)(x + 4) = 0$$\nThis gives us two possible solutions for $x$:\n$$x = 9 \\quad \\text{or} \\quad x = -4$$\n\nStep 4: Check the solutions for $x$\nIf $x = 9$:\n$$y^2 = 5(9)$$\n$$y^2 = 45$$\n$$y = \\pm 3\\sqrt{5}$$\n\nIf $x = -4$:\n$$y^2 = 5(-4)$$\n$$y^2 = -20$$\n$$y = \\pm 2i\\sqrt{5}$$\n\nHowever, since $y$ must be a real number, $x = 9$ is the only valid solution.\n\nThus, the value of $x$ is $\\boxed{9}$.\n\n### Explanation\nWe began by using logarithmic properties to simplify the given equations. Then, we converted each logarithmic equation to an exponential form, which led us to a system of equations. Solving this system, we found two possible values for $x$, but only one, $x = 9$, satisfied the conditions of real and positive $y$ values.\n\nWait, let me recheck my solution.\n\n'[0m
